headline: Starbucks sales grow, Chipotle's consumer woes: Earnings takeaways
summary: Chipotle Mexican Grill (CMG) stock continues to sink lower in Thursday's session after its third quarter revenue fell just short of estimates, it cut its full-year guidance again, and the company noted pull backs in low to middle-income consumers. Meanwhile, Starbucks (SBUX) stock appears unfazed as the coffee giant published global same-store sales growth amid CEO Brian Niccol's turnaround plan. Yahoo Finance senior consumer reporter Brooke DiPalma highlights the biggest takeaways and stock moves from the two companies' latest earnings reports. headline: 'Back to Starbucks' Turnaround Plan Is Working, CEO Niccol Says
summary: Starbucks Corp. Chief Executive Officer Brian Niccol says the "Back to Starbucks" plan is working to drive sales and improve service. Sales at established locations rose 1% in the most recent quarter. He talks about renovating restaurants, how more customers are adding protein to their drinks, adding workers, and growing the business in China. He speaks to Bloomberg's Romaine Bostick.

headline: Chipotle stock dives on consumer woes. Why Starbucks was unfazed.
summary: Chipotle (CMG) stock tumbles after CEO Scott Boatwright reported that middle to low-income consumers are dining out less frequently due to worries about the economy, with 25 to 35-year-old customers being especially challenged. Despite the burrito maker citing macroeconomic concerns, Starbucks (SBUX) — which also released earnings — didn't say it is facing the same consumer spending changes. Yahoo Finance Senior Reporter Brooke DiPalma outlines the details, as Crossmark Global Investments chief market strategist Victoria Fernandez examines why Starbucks didn't echo Chipotle's consumer spending challenges. headline: Starbucks Stock Drops. Earnings Offer a Glimpse at Company’s Turnaround Plans.
summary: Starbucks  reported fiscal fourth-quarter earnings that fell short of expectations.  Starbucks’ adjusted earnings of 52 cents a share came in below consensus estimates calling for 56 cents a share, according to FactSet.  Unadjusted operating margins fell 11.5 percentage points year over year, partially because of investments in more labor hours, as well as costs associated with closing coffeehouses—Starbucks shuttered 107 stores throughout the quarter.
